# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bob-melvin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The **1980 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1980 NCAA Division I baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its thirty fourth year.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] Eight regional competitions were held to determine the participants in the final event.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] Seven regions held a four team, double-elimination tournament while one region included six teams, resulting in 34 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The thirty-fourth tournament's champion was Arizona, coached by Jerry Kindall.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The Most Outstanding Player was Terry Francona of the Arizona.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] Seven of the eight regionals were played as 4-team double-elimination tournaments.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] One regional was played as a 6-team double-elimination tournament.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The winner of each regional moved onto the College World Series.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] Games played in Clemson, South Carolina.
[src:bob-melvin/1980-college-world-series] The following players were members of the All-Tournament Team.
[src:bob-melvin/1981-major-league-baseball-draft] The **1981 Major League Baseball draft** took place in June 1981.
[src:bob-melvin/1981-major-league-baseball-draft] The draft saw the Seattle Mariners select Mike Moore first overall.
[src:bob-melvin/1981-major-league-baseball-draft] The following are the first round picks in the 1981 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] The **1985 Major League Baseball season** ended with the Kansas City Royals defeating the St.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the seventh game of the I-70 World Series.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] Bret Saberhagen, the regular season Cy Young Award winner, was named MVP of the Series.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won the All-Star Game for the second straight year.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first full season for Peter Ueberroth as commissioner.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] The 56th All-Star Game was played on July 16 at the Metrodome in Minneapolis, the home of the Minnesota Twins, with the National League winning 6–1.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] There was a brief interruption during the regular season.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] The 1985 Major League Baseball strike occurred August 6 and 7, lasting only two days.
[src:bob-melvin/1985-major-league-baseball-season] The 25 cancelled games were for the most part made up later on in the season on open dates or parts of doubleheaders.
[src:bob-melvin/1986-major-league-baseball-season] The **1986 Major League Baseball season** saw the New York Mets win their second World Series title, their first since 1969.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The **1988 Major League Baseball season** ended with the underdog Los Angeles Dodgers shocking the Oakland Athletics, who had won 104 games during the regular season, in the World Series.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The most memorable moment of the series came in Game 1, when injured Dodger Kirk Gibson hit a dramatic pinch-hit walk-off home run off Athletics closer Dennis Eckersley to win the game for Los Angeles.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers went on to win the Series in five games.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] This would also be the final full season for Peter Ueberroth as MLB commissioner.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] One of the American League's best players in 1988 was Athletics outfielder José Canseco, who became the first player in history to hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a single season, unanimously garnering league MVP honors.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The A's surrounded him with a stellar supporting cast, led by fellow slugger Mark McGwire (with whom Canseco formed the famed "Bash Brothers" duo).
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Aided by strong pitching from Dave Stewart and Bob Welch and the lights-out Eckersley securing 45 saves, Oakland ran away with the American League West and swept the Boston Red Sox of Boggs, Rice, and Clemens in the playoffs before falling to the Dodgers in the World Series.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Speaking of the Dodgers, nobody expected them even to contend for the National League West title in 1988, let alone win the World Championship.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] However, the intensity and clutch hitting of Gibson (named the NL MVP at season's end) and the solid pitching of Orel Hershiser (who won a league-leading 23 games) spearheaded L.A. to a division championship by seven games over the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] In addition to his 23 victories, Hershiser led the National League with 267 innings pitched and 8 shutouts, and also set a record of 59 consecutive scoreless innings (formerly held by Dodger great Don Drysdale).
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] These accomplishments, combined with his 2.26 ERA, earned him the National League Cy Young Award.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] However, it was in the postseason that Hershiser really distinguished himself – he started Games 1 and 3 of the NLCS against the tough New York Mets, saved Game 4 in relief, and threw a complete-game shutout in Game 7.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] He hurled another complete-game shutout in Game 2 of the World Series and also helped his own cause, going 3-for-3 at the plate with a run scored and an RBI, and again went the distance in the clinching Game 5.
[src:bob-melvin/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Hershiser was named MVP of both the NLCS and the World Series, capping off arguably one of the greatest seasons a starting pitcher has ever had.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The **1989 Major League Baseball season** saw the Oakland Athletics win their first World Series title since 1974.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The American League saw the Oakland Athletics and the Toronto Blue Jays as the AL West and AL East division winners, respectively.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] Oakland dominated the entire American League with their second straight season of more than 100 wins (including postseason wins) and looked to be a future dynasty.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The Blue Jays, powered by their offense, won their division title in the final weekend of the season.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants stole the spotlight in the National League, but the Giants proved to be more dominant with a strong hitting presence, while the Cubs extended their streak without a World Series championship to 81 years.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last season under the television contracts with ABC and NBC.
[src:bob-melvin/1989-major-league-baseball-season] MLB signed new deals with CBS and ESPN to begin broadcasting games in 1990.
[src:bob-melvin/1991-major-league-baseball-season] The **1991 Major League Baseball season** saw the Minnesota Twins defeat the Atlanta Braves for the World Series title, in a series where every game was won by the home team.
[src:bob-melvin/1991-major-league-baseball-season] The Twins and Braves became the first two teams in MLB history to win the pennant after finishing last the previous season.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In his 21-year managing career Melvin has led the Seattle Mariners (2003–04), Arizona Diamondbacks (2005–09), Oakland Athletics (2011–21), San Diego Padres (2022–23), and San Francisco Giants (2024–2025).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was named the National League Manager of the Year in 2007, and the American League Manager of the Year in both 2012 (becoming the sixth manager in history to win the award in both leagues) and in 2018 (becoming the eighth manager ever to win the award at least three times).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Entering the 2020 MLB season, Melvin was the longest-tenured manager in MLB with the same team.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Through 2023, his 853 Oakland wins were second-most in team history (behind Connie Mack).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He had an aggregate career record of 1,678–1,588 (.514) in 21 seasons as a Major League manager and led his clubs to eight postseason appearances and four division titles; he has made the League Championship Series twice, losing each time.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Robert Paul Melvin was born on October 28, 1961, in Palo Alto, California, to Paul and Judy (Levitas) Melvin, and grew up in Menlo Park, California.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The son of a Jewish mother (who raised him after his parents divorced in 1972) and a Catholic father.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He would later recall celebrating Passover with his mother's family.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] "Bud" Levitas, was the original ballboy in the 1920s for the Acme Packers (precursor to the Green Bay Packers), and later married Melvin's maternal grandmother, Leah Levitas, who died in 2007.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] After attending Laurel and Encinal elementary schools in Menlo Park, Melvin played baseball (at catcher), basketball (at forward), and golf at Menlo-Atherton High School in Atherton, south of San Francisco, graduating in 1979.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He batted .474 with 11 home runs for the baseball team, including .529 his senior year when he was named to the *San Jose Mercury News'* All-Central Coast Section baseball team.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He was the first student inducted into the school's Hall of Fame.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin then enrolled at the University of California in Berkeley, and played catcher for the Golden Bears.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] As a freshman, he helped lead Cal to a 44–23–1 (.654) record and a third-place finish at the College World Series in 1980.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin finished his freshman season batting .269 with two doubles and 12 RBIs in 67 at bats over 29 games.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Following his freshman year at California, Melvin transferred to Cañada College in Redwood City, California.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He played fall ball for the baseball team.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was selected in the 1st round (2nd pick) by the Detroit Tigers in the secondary phase of the 1981 draft.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He debuted in the major leagues on May 25, 1985, at the age of 23.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He played 11 seasons, mostly as a back-up catcher, for the Tigers, San Francisco Giants, Baltimore Orioles, Kansas City Royals, Boston Red Sox, New York Yankees, and Chicago White Sox.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] As a Tiger, he backed up Lance Parrish, and as a Giant, he served as the backup for fellow catcher Bob Brenly, who, like him, went on to manage the Diamondbacks.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] During his winters in San Francisco, he interned at Bear Stearns.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 1987, he caught stealing 42.9% of attempted base-stealers, second-best in the National League.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 1991, Melvin turned five double plays at catcher, fifth-most in the American League, despite playing in only 79 games.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin finished his career with a batting average of .233, and 35 home runs.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin worked for Milwaukee as a scout in 1996, roving instructor in 1997, and assistant to General Manager Sal Bando in 1998.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He began his coaching career as Manager Phil Garner's bench coach from 1999 to 2000, first with the Brewers in 1999 wearing #12 (during which time he also managed the Maryvale team in the Arizona Fall League), and then in 2000 with the Tigers, wearing #15.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He was inducted into the AFL Hall of Fame in 2013.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin then served the Arizona Diamondbacks as bench coach on the staff of manager Bob Brenly, from 2001 to 2002, a period in which the team won two NL West titles, as well as the 2001 World Series.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On February 19, 2026, the Athletics hired Melvin to serve as a special assistant within the organization's baseball operations department.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin managed the Seattle Mariners in 2003 and 2004, following a ten-year run of Lou Piniella.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Mariners won 93 games with a .574 win–loss percentage in 2003, as the 93 wins tied Melvin for the 15th-most by any rookie manager in Major League history.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] However, the team missed the playoffs, finishing three games behind the Oakland Athletics in the division, and two behind the Boston Red Sox for the one wild card spot.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The following season was less successful, as the Mariners lost 99 games in 2004, and Melvin's contract was not extended.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He finished with a 156–168 career record (.481) as Mariners manager.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He returned to the Diamondbacks for whom he previously had been bench coach before being hired by the Mariners.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was the second manager the Diamondbacks hired for 2005, after they fired Wally Backman before he managed a single game due to revelations of his past arrests and serious financial troubles.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin led the team on a 26-game improvement from a franchise-worst 51–111 mark in 2004, as the team finished 2005 with a record of 77–85.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin led Arizona to a National League West title in 2007 with a record of 90–72, and a .556 win–loss percentage.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Diamondbacks entered the playoffs as the No.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They swept the Chicago Cubs in the NLDS, but then were swept themselves in the NLCS by the Colorado Rockies.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was named National League *Sporting News* Manager of the Year and MLB Manager of the Year for 2007.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] His nickname was "The Mad Scientist", because of his mental approach to the game.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On August 14, 2008, with his 304th win Melvin became the winningest manager in Arizona history, passing Bob Brenly.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was fired as manager and replaced by A.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Hinch, another former catcher, after the May 8, 2009, game.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin finished with a 337–340 regular season record as Diamondbacks manager, and a 3–4 post–season record.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Following the 2009 season, Melvin was a candidate to be the next manager of the Houston Astros.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] However, the position was filled by Brad Mills.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He was interviewed by the Milwaukee Brewers for their managerial opening in October 2010, and was believed to be a finalist along with Bobby Valentine, Joey Cora, and Ron Roenicke.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The position eventually went to Roenicke, then the Angels' bench coach.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2010, Melvin was a scout for the New York Mets, and in May 2011 he worked for the Diamondbacks as a special baseball advisor to president and CEO Derrick Hall.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On June 9, 2011, Melvin was named interim manager of the Oakland Athletics following Bob Geren's dismissal.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On September 21, he was given the managerial position on a permanent basis, with a three-year contract extension, and became the 30th manager in franchise history, and the 18th in Oakland history.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Athletics fashioned a 47–52 record under Melvin's watch, and a 74–88 overall finish to 2011.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2011, he had the lowest rate of his pitchers issuing intentional walks per game of all AL managers, at 0.2%.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin went on the *Chris Townsend Show* in the Bay Area after the first game of the 2012 season in Tokyo, and promised the fans that the Athletics would work hard every game.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He managed the Athletics to the franchise's best-ever record in July at 19–5.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On October 1, the Athletics clinched their first playoff appearance since 2006, and two days later clinched the American League West.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] For the regular season, the team was 94–68, a .580 win–loss percentage.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2012, he used the fewest pinch runners per game of all AL managers, at 0.10.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Athletics faced the Detroit Tigers in the Division Series.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They lost the first two games in close fashion before going back to Oakland and winning tight affairs in Game 3 and 4 to force a pivotal Game 5 in Oakland.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They were then shut out 6–0 to finish the series.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Melvin was honored as the 2012 American League Manager of the Year.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He became the 14th manager in history to win the award at least twice in a career, and the sixth manager to win the award in both leagues.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] During the 2013 season, Melvin's second full season at the helm, the Athletics continued what began the previous year, posting winning records for every month of the season and securing a second consecutive American League West Division Championship.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Athletics' outfielder Josh Reddick referred to Melvin as the "King of Platoons" due to his extensive use of platoons.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In the 2013 regular season, the team was 96–66 with a .593 win–loss percentage.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They then faced the Tigers in the Division Series.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Oakland won two of the first three games and even had Game 5 set up in Oakland.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They lost Game 4 and then were shutout in Game 5 to once again lose at home.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2014, Melvin's Athletics entered the All-Star Break with the best record in the majors.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] While the team faded down the stretch, it still managed to clinch an AL Wild Card berth on the final day of the season.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They played the Kansas City Royals in the 2014 American League Wild Card Game.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They held a 7–3 at the end of seven innings but Melvin ran into trouble when starter Jon Lester (coming up to 100 pitches) allowed a series of hits, a pair of stolen bases (made worse with the loss of catcher Geovany Soto to injury) and a walk that made the score 7–4 with two runners on base.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Only then did Melvin decide to finally take out Lester (at 111 pitches), after which the bullpen gave up two further runs in the inning but Oakland still led 7–6 in the ninth inning.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Further timely baserunning and hits led to more unraveling as the game went into extra innings on a tying 9th inning run.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Athletics even led 8–7 in the bottom of the 12th but gave up the lead and lost on a walk-off single.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2015, Melvin only had his players place eleven sacrifice bunts, the lowest number in the AL.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On July 29, 2017, he became the 64th MLB manager to win 1,000 games in his career.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On September 28, 2017, the Athletics and Melvin agreed to extend his contract through the 2019 season.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2017, he used the most pinch hitters per game of any AL manager (0.79), and the fewest pinch runners per game (0.12).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On October 29, 2018, the Athletics awarded Melvin a long-term contract extension, through 2021 with a club option for 2022.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On November 13, 2018, Melvin won his third Manager of the Year award, becoming just the 8th manager in MLB history to win the award three times.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] He won the award after leading the baseball team with the lowest Opening Day payroll to a 97–65 record and its first post-season in four years.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2019, he used the fewest pinch runners per game of all AL managers, at 0.07.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On June 1, 2021; with a 12–6 win over the Seattle Mariners, Melvin tallied his 798th win as Athletics manager.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] This vaulted him past Tony La Russa to become the second-winningest manager in Athletics history, and the winningest in the West Coast portion of franchise history.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2021 he led all AL managers with an average of 0.99 pinch hitters per game.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] By the end of his Athletics tenure, his 853 wins were second-most in team history, behind only Hall of Fame manager Connie Mack.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] His 1,346 wins ranked 34th in MLB history.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Among active Major League managers, only Dusty Baker, and Terry Francona had more wins.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In Oakland, he had led them to six postseason appearances and three division titles; the Athletics lost in the first round in five of their six postseason appearances, winning just the 2020 AL Wild Card Series before losing in the 2020 ALDS.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On November 1, 2021, Melvin became the 22nd manager of the San Diego Padres.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In his first season as manager, Melvin led the Padres to the postseason, the Padres first playoff berth in a full season since 2006.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In the Wild Card Series, against the New York Mets, the Padres defeated the Mets 2–1 to advance.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Under Melvin, the Padres defeated the 111-win Los Angeles Dodgers three-games-to-one in the 2022 National League Division Series, but lost the league championship series to the Philadelphia Phillies 4 games to 1.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] That season, he had the team issue the lowest rate of intentional walks in the league (in 0.1% of plate appearances).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2023, Melvin led the Padres to a record of 82-80.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] They finished third in the NL West, one spot ahead of the 79-83 Giants.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] His 1,517 regular season wins ranked 25th all-time and were third-most among active managers behind Bruce Bochy (2,093) and Buck Showalter (1,727).
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] One of 15 managers with eight postseason appearances in MLB history, Melvin is the only one to have never won a league pennant.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On October 25, 2023, Melvin was hired as the 39th manager of the San Francisco Giants, signing a three-year contract with the club.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In his first season, the Giants finished with an 80–82 record.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] On July 1, 2025, the Giants exercised Melvin's option for 2026.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] In 2025, despite a major midseason acquisition of Rafael Devers, the Giants finished with an 81–81 record, only a one-win improvement from the last season and two games out of the final wild card spot.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The Giants fired Melvin at the conclusion of the season, finishing his tenure in San Francisco with a 161–163 (.497) record in two seasons.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Through 2021, he was one of seven Jewish managers in MLB history.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] The others were Gabe Kapler, Brad Ausmus, Jeff Newman, Norm Sherry, Lefty Phillips, and Lipman Pike.
[src:bob-melvin/bob-melvin] Bob has one daughter, Alexi (born in 1988), who is an actress, Melvin and his daughter are actively involved with the Juvenile Diabetes Research Foundation; Alexi was diagnosed with juvenile diabetes at age 14.
